There may be 20 or more Starbucks in this area of the city alone.

Considering the fact that at 7.30am there is very little that is open in Sheung Wan or Central districts when it comes to Western restaurants, bakeries and smaller specialised coffee shops - and one quickly understands why you encounter so many Starbucks in this area of the city.

We sometimes stop by Starbucks shops along Des Voeux Road before making way into the nearby Central MTR station. Staff seem to always speak English very well and are polite. In the morning, the pastries counter is always full so little risk of them having sold out of food you might like to order. Lastly, Starbucks coffee is consistent and predictable, nothing great but fair enough, especially their espressos.

Another reason I don't mind visiting Starbucks in the morning is that their seating area is clean, tables are available and the music played is nice. The former is not often the case later in the day when the crowds have hit the streets of Hong Kong.

In the end, its Starbucks. Like the situation in Manhattan where you seem to find them at every street corner, the coffee giant has its place in Hong Kong in this day and age. [{'author_name': 'ssg', 'author_url': 'https://www.google.com/maps/contrib/114154887650952138673/reviews', 'language': 'en', 'original_language': 'en', 'profile_photo_url': 'https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a-/AD_cMMQcuqQGxbrW0yH6DLkNGS620HqpCtAd-HjhHK47Gw=s128-c0x00000000-cc-rp-mo-ba8', 'rating': 3, 'relative_time_description': '2 years ago', 'text': "As I was in the area, I discovered that this whole building belonged to the Maxims group so went in there out of curiosity and discovered a Starbucks.

There is another restaurant on the 1st floor but it is only for Maxim's staff.

As it was lunch had the meatball and potato pie, pancakes and Chocolate red tea latte.

The meatball and potato pie was held in a flakey tart base and it was filled with rich tangy tomato sauce which was also quite sweet at the same time.

The meatballs in the pie were quite nice as it had lots of herbs and tasted more like sausage meat.

You could tell the pancakes were pre made and taken from a stack and heated as they were neatly stuck together in a pile.

They were a bit dry and sweet but dipping it in the drink made it more palatable.

Finished with the Chocolate red tea which was rather sweet and the chocolate was more prominent than the tea so I didn't really like it.", 'time': 1599170315, 'translated': False}, {'author_name': 'Darren Gilkison', 'author_url': 'https://www.google.com/maps/contrib/115114072321762307977/reviews', 'language': 'en', 'original_language': 'en', 'profile_photo_url': 'https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a/AAcHTtcvcQzOylm_ZkIxrxzGmxU9TpkFnEfK6bxXuyjU=s128-c0x00000000-cc-rp-mo', 'rating': 5, 'relative_time_description': '8 months ago', 'text': 'Outstanding customer service and the food is always fresh!', 'time': 1663807814, 'translated': False}]

[{'author_name': 'BradJill', 'author_url': 'https://www.google.com/maps/contrib/117832408789555351833/reviews', 'language': 'en', 'original_language': 'en', 'profile_photo_url': 'https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a-/AD_cMMTaVBZj_F9hXVP6S2M_NBqMzM6tjGK-tMDcu1w_=s128-c0x00000000-cc-rp-mo-ba8', 'rating': 3, 'relative_time_description': '2 months ago', 'text': "This Starbucks used to be located on the G/F on the south end of V City not far from the MTR entrance. They relocated to 1/F at the north end of the mall recently and in their old spot, you will now find a local coffee shop called Cupping Room. The relocated Starbucks has the same opening hours as before, 7.30am to 9pm daily. The seating area is smaller now, same counter foods, coffee and non-coffee list that you will find at all their branches around the city.

Tuen Mun has been a bit slow to join the fast evolving coffee shop scene around the rest of the city. There are a few local places in Tuen Mun that are pretty good. I like White Goats on Yan Oi Tong Circuit not terribly far from here and would target this place before Starbucks without hesitation.
